<node TEXT="JVM" LOCALIZED_STYLE_REF="AutomaticLayout.level,2" ID="ID_351909733" CREATED="1553506890371" MODIFIED="1553871183255"><richcontent TYPE="DETAILS" HIDDEN="true">

<html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); display: inline !important; float: none"><font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size="13px">JVM (Java Virtual Machine) is an abstract machine. It is called a virtual machine because it doesn't physically exist. It is a specification that provides a runtime environment in which Java bytecode can be executed. It can also run those programs which are written in other languages and compiled to Java bytecode. </font></span>
    </p>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <p>
      <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); display: inline !important; float: none"><font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size="13px">JVMs are available for many hardware and software platforms. JVM, JRE, and JDK are platform dependent because the configuration of each</font></span><font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size="13px"><span>&#160;</span></font><a href="https://www.javatpoint.com/os-tutorial" style="color: green; text-decoration: none; font-family: verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255)"><font color="green" face="verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size="13px">OS</font></a><span><font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size="13px">&#160;</font></span><font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size="13px"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); display: inline !important; float: none">is different from each other. However, Java is platform independent. There are three notions of the JVM:</span><span>&#160;</span><em style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255)">specification</em><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); display: inline !important; float: none">,</span><span>&#160;</span><em style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255)">implementation</em><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); display: inline !important; float: none">, and</span><span>&#160;</span><em style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255)">instance</em><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); display: inline !important; float: none">. </span></font>
    </p>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <p>
      <font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif">&#160;.Its implementation has been provided by Oracle and other companies. Its implementation is known as JRE. </font>
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jvms/se8/html/">impelentation</a>
    </p>
  </body>
</html>
</richcontent>
<node TEXT="JRE" ID="ID_253579684" CREATED="1553507454281" MODIFIED="1553535316113"><richcontent TYPE="DETAILS" HIDDEN="true">

<html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      <font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif">JRE stands for Java Runtime Environment. It is the implementation of JVM. The Java Runtime Environment is a set of software tools which are used for developing Java applications. It is used to provide the runtime environment. It is the implementation of JVM. It physically exists. It contains a set of libraries + other files that JVM uses at runtime. </font>
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="https://www.javatpoint.com/internal-details-of-hello-java-program">link</a>
    </p>
  </body>
</html>
</richcontent>
