<node TEXT="Stack" ID="ID_436640251" CREATED="1553792475149" MODIFIED="1553871042430"><richcontent TYPE="DETAILS" HIDDEN="true">

<html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255)">
      Java Stack stores frames. It holds local variables and partial results, and plays a part in method invocation and return.
    </p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255)">
      Each thread has a private JVM stack, created at the same time as thread.
    </p>
    <p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255)">
      A new frame is created each time a method is invoked. A frame is destroyed when its method invocation completes.
    </p>
  </body>
</html>
</richcontent>
</node>
