<node TEXT="HashSet" ID="ID_1650657714" CREATED="1552025071970" MODIFIED="1554212424847"><richcontent TYPE="DETAILS" HIDDEN="true">

<html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      <font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">&#160;</font><a class="APILink" target="_blank" href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/HashSet.html" style="text-decoration: none; color: rgb(58, 135, 207); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8px; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px"><font color="rgb(58, 135, 207)" face="Monaco, Courier, Courier New" size="12.8px"><code style="font-family: Monaco, Courier, Courier New">HashSet</code></font></a><font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">, which stores its elements in a hash table, is the best-performing implementation; however it makes no guarantees concerning the order of iteration.&#160; </font>
    </p>
    <p>
      This class implements the Set interface, backed by a hash table (actually a HashMap instance). It makes no guarantees as to the iteration order of the set; in particular, it does not guarantee that the order will remain constant over time. <font color="#ff3366">This class permits the null element.</font>
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/HashSet.html">link</a>
    </p>
  </body>
</html>

